Amazon E-K-S: managed Kubernetes.

E-C-S covers the vast majority of new container workloads. Three situations push you toward E-K-S instead. The first is an existing Kubernetes investment, where you want one operational model across all your environments. The second is multi-cloud or on-premises portability, because Kubernetes manifests are largely cloud-agnostic, while E-C-S task definitions are not. And the third is rich Kubernetes-specific needs, like taints, tolerations, custom controllers, Helm charts, service meshes, and GitOps tooling.

E-K-S runs the Kubernetes control plane, the A-P-I server, etcd, scheduler, and controller manager, as a managed service, at about ten cents an hour per cluster. You own the worker nodes, through three options. Managed Node Groups, where AWS handles the E-C-2 lifecycle, are the sensible default. Self-Managed Nodes, with your own A-M-I and Auto Scaling Group, are for custom A-M-Is, Windows, or kernel-level requirements. And a Fargate Profile means no E-C-2 at all: pods matching a namespace and label selector run on Fargate. E-K-S on Fargate has real trade-offs, though: no DaemonSets, no privileged containers, no E-B-S-backed volumes, though E-F-S works, and no G-P-U support.

The choice comes down to whether Kubernetes is a real requirement, not just a preference. Default to E-C-S on Fargate for new AWS-only workloads; it's the simplest, cheapest, lowest-overhead path. Reach for E-K-S when you already run Kubernetes, need portability, or need its scheduler and ecosystem. The control-plane cost and operational complexity earn their place then.
